==Regular season== *October 5: The Wisconsin Badgers womenâs hockey team was ranked No. 4 in the country. The USCHO.com officials revealed it in their first Top-10 Womenâs Hockey Poll of the season. Wisconsin accumulated 112 points and one first place vote.<ref>http://hurstathletics.com/news/2009/10/5/WHOCK_1005094806.aspx</ref>
*January 5: In an exhibition game against Wisconsin, former Wisconsin player Jinelle Zaugg-Siergiej netted a goal and had an assist as the American Olympic Hockey Team won by a score of 9-0.<ref>http://www.waow.com/Global/story.asp?S=11775488 </ref>
*The Wisconsin women's team will play host to the Camp Randall Hockey Classic on Feb. 6, 2010 at Camp Randall Stadium. The UW women's hockey program will take on the Bemidji State Beavers outdoors at the stadium as part of their weekend series, while the men's program will follow against the Michigan Wolverines in what will serve as the United States Hockey Hall of Fame Game.<ref>http://www.wcha.com/sports/m-hockey/spec-rel/030609aaa.html</ref>
*Feb 6: The No. 9 Wisconsin womenâs hockey team (16-10-3, 13-9-1 WCHA) defeated the Bemidji State Beavers (8-14-7, 7-9-7 WCHA), 6-1, in the first ever Culverâs Camp Randall Hockey Classic at [[Camp Randall Stadium]]. The Badgers played in front of an NCAA-record crowd of 8,263 fans in the second-ever womenâs hockey outdoor showdown. Sophomore Carolyne Prevost scored the first goal in Camp Randall history at the 16:53 mark and backhanded it in to put the Badgers up 1-0. The Badgers dominated offensively, outshooting the Beavers 42-13. Freshman Becca Ruegsegger (Lakewood, Colo.) finished with 13 saves in net for Wisconsin,<ref> http://www.uwbadgers.com/sports/w-hockey/recaps/020610aaa.html</ref>
